# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: doc-adams
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the years 1845 to 1868 throughout the world.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] At its December 1868 annual meeting, the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP) permitted professional clubs.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Twelve existing members did "go pro" and constitute the professional field for 1869.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1868 season records for 98 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 15 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors" (not marked), all of the 1869 "pros" (*), all 14 member clubs with at least twelve wins on record, and a few others.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the seven listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] At least four Association clubs not listed here would someday try professionalism: Riverside of Portsmouth, Ohio (1870); Kekionga of Fort Wayne, Indiana (1871); Middletown of Mansfield, Connecticut (1872); Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey (1873).
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Meanwhile, only two brand new professional baseball clubs would be established in the next three years, the Chicago White Stockings for 1870 and the Boston Red Stockings for 1871.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Their commercial origins may be related to their survival alone by 1877, and on to 2010, while all of their rivals with older and amateur roots fell away.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1867 season records for 89 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 17 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 13 member clubs with at least fourteen wins on record, and a few others.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the nine listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Star (*) marks ten clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Excelsior of Chicago and Buckeye of Cincinnati are listed because they were probably the strongest teams in the west after the Cincinnati Red Stockings.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1866 season records for 58 of 93 association members, said to be complete for games between two member clubs.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 20 of that season's teams "major" including three old New York rivals of the Knickerbockers.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 14 members with at least eight wins on record, and a few others.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the fifteen listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Star (*) marks eight clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869, three seasons later.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the preceding 1865 season Marshall Wright lists 30 members with supposedly complete records for most of them.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Twenty-two of the thirty were in Greater New York.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 19 teams "major" in the first season that he covers: sixteen of the members and three others (Lowell, Harvard, and Camden).
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] No one traveled much and membership was still depressed by the Civil War.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] There had been 59 delegates at the March 1860 annual meeting, and 55 at the next annual meeting that December (on a new baseball calendar), who thereby intended to play during the 1861 season that the war curtailed.
[src:doc-adams/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Nine of 59 and eleven of 55 were from outside Greater New York.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The **1857 baseball convention** was a meeting of members from 16 New York City-area baseball clubs that took place over multiple sessions in early 1857.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] It passed numerous clarifications of the pre-existing Knickerbocker Rules and modifications that helped lead to the modern format of baseball games.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Among the items formalized were the length of games and the distance between bases.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] At the convention, multiple members of the New York Knickerbockers club presented the "Laws of Base Ball", a series of documents that contained proposed rules, some of which were edited in response to feedback.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The law documents drafted for the convention survived and were sold at auction for more than $3 million in 2016.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] After the pioneering New York Knickerbockers club was founded in 1845, baseball grew slowly at first in the New York City area.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] However, by 1855 it had started to accelerate in popularity, as two dozen teams were in existence that year.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The nature of games played between the teams changed during the period.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] While early Knickerbockers games functioned mainly as social events that allowed players to exercise and fraternize with other players, by 1855, competitive match games had grown more frequent.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] As a result, the existing rules proved inadequate in addressing various situations that arose in competitive play.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] While opposing teams agreed upon their own match rules, which led to changes in common practices, a uniform code of regulations was lacking.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Even items such as the types of balls and bats to be used were not standardized.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The rules also had aspects that could be taken advantage of in unintended ways that went against the spirit of the game.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Meanwhile, new clubs often wrote into sports columns in newspapers asking for clarifications on rules.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Another factor driving the push was the general improvement of fielding skills, which at the time was the most crucial aspect of the game.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The original Knickerbocker Rules, which the Knickerbockers used for internal play, dated back to 1845, with small adjustments made three years later.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Following an 1854 meeting involving three teams—the Eagles, Gothams, and Knickerbockers—a set of match play guidelines were coded to address rules differences between the clubs.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] One year later, with the increase in match play accelerating, the idea of a convention addressing the rules was floated, but the Knickerbockers were not involved in the efforts, which proved futile.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] By 1856, the Knickerbockers were ready to participate, and in December of that year a call for a convention was made.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The Knickerbockers took the lead in organizing the convention, as the team held an internal meeting on December 6, 1856.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] It formed a three-man committee led by Doc Adams to accomplish the task of gaining attendance from New York City-area clubs.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Sixteen clubs agreed to participate in the convention, which was held over at least two sessions.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The first took place on January 22, 1857, while the second was held about a month later, on February 25.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Press advertisements indicated that a session would be held on February 3, but no records of any committee activities having taken place on that date are known to exist.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Of the 16 clubs, 14 sent representatives to the first meeting.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The other two teams sent members to the second session, but not all representatives from the first session returned.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] As a result, neither session had attendance from every team.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] At the January 22 meeting of the convention, which was held in a Broome Street hotel, each of the 14 attending clubs sent three delegates.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The teams started by naming officers; Adams was selected as president.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] A handful of other officers from varying teams were named.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The convention saw the Knickerbockers present a series of documents collectively titled the "Laws of Base Ball", which had been drafted in 1856.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Adams probably wrote one of the documents himself, according to historian John Thorn, while fellow Knickerbocker William Grenelle contributed a second Laws paper and a document titled "Rules for Match Games of Base Ball", which contained playing ground guidelines not addressed elsewhere.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The papers were then edited and put together prior to the convention.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Some of the papers Grenelle contributed have visible penciled changes, from a different writer; Thorn believes that Adams made the edits.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The Knickerbockers did not initially gain approval for the drafts; instead, a rules committee was appointed to meet on January 28; the attending clubs each sent one delegate.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Other items discussed at the first meeting included the possibility of a baseball field being built in Central Park, which led to the appointment of a five-member lobbying committee, and the delegates voted to charge clubs a $2 assessment.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] When the rules committee met on January 28, William H.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Van Cott, a member of the Gothams, was named chairman.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The Knickerbockers' proposal was discussed, and a final draft was made to present during the second full meeting of the committee.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Some of the items were amended after floor motions, but the resulting version was ultimately approved.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] One of the major items addressed in the Laws was the prescribed length of games.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Under the Knickerbocker Rules, games did not have a set number of innings, instead concluding when a team reached 21 runs.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] This method left potential issues regarding match play, as was evidenced by an 1856 game between the Knickerbockers and the Empire club; each team scored 21 runs over eight innings and the game ended in a tie.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] This was not the only factor that threatened to prevent matches from having winners.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] As match play became more widespread in the mid-1850s, teams improved and contests became closer and lower-scoring in nature.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Under practices of the time, in the event that neither team scored 21 runs before darkness or inclement weather forced a stoppage of play, a game ended in a draw.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Teams seeking to play for a stalemate could easily do so by not swinging at pitches, as no system of calling balls and strikes existed.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The "Match Games" document originally indicated that games should last 12 innings, but the number was changed to nine during editing.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The issue resulted in a divide between the Knickerbockers and club delegates Adams and Louis Wadsworth; the team had supported seven-inning games, but Adams and Wadsworth sought longer contests.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Although *Porter*'s stated that the shorter game length had won support at the convention, nine-inning games were decided upon, following a motion by Wadsworth.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Also in the rules was a provision that, should a game be suspended due to weather, the leading team would be declared the winner if five innings had been played; these new rules served to remove the possibility of draws.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The convention also brought clarity to the topic of the distance between bases.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Previously, the distance had been listed as 42 paces between first base and third base, and from second base to home plate.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The actual distance depended upon the definition of "pace"; a two-and-a-half foot pace would have resulted in a distance of around 75 feet, while a person actually pacing out the steps could lead to inconsistencies.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Adams later wrote that the pre-existing standard "was rather vague".
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] In the Rules document, he and Grenelle changed the definition of a baseball field to focus on the overall basepath.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The first page of Rules prescribed a 42-yard distance between first and third bases, and second base and home plate, which would have resulted in bases being 89.1 feet apart.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Before the convention, a change was made that Thorn called "a small step, but one of simple genius".
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The distance between bases was set at 90 feet, leaving 127 feet between second base and home plate.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] In the Laws document, Adams also took a step to provide more precise specifications for how far the pitcher would stand from home plate.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] While the laws originally called for a distance of 15 to 16 yards, depending on where the pitcher decided to stand, he changed the document to set the distance at 45 feet.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Dating back to 1854, the previous regulations had merely called for the pitcher to be "not less than fifteen paces" from home plate, leaving open the possibility of pitchers positioning themselves off-center when throwing.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] To restrict the possible location, section 5 of the rules specified that the position be inside "a line four yard in length, drawn at right angles to a line from home to the second base, having a center upon that line".
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] As had been the case in 1845 rules, the document provided that balks could be called against pitchers, subject to the judgement of umpires, which would result in all baserunners moving up one base.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] One field regulation likely added due to input from the convention floor was a regulation restricting where batters could stand.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] It prevented batters from standing behind home plate; had the committee's draft not been tweaked, weakly hit balls would have had a greater chance of being foul balls.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Early baseball bats could be either round or flat.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Section 2 of the Laws document mandated the use of round bats, which were to be made of wood and limited to a maximum diameter of two inches.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The Knickerbockers' original draft had permitted one side of the bat to be shaved flat in a manner similar to a cricket bat, which according to the document was meant to allow for improved aiming on batted balls.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] For unknown reasons, this part of the draft failed to make it through the rules committee.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The rules also addressed the size of the baseball, calling for balls to be between 6 and 6.5 ounces in weight, and between 10 and 10.25 inches in circumference.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Both sets of numbers were increased from the 1854 rules, although balls meeting the older guidelines ended up closer to modern equivalents.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] A surge in interest from gamblers, as well as the existence of loopholes for clubs to take advantage of existing player eligibility regulations, led to responses in the 1857 rules.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] A new addition in the Laws documents, in section 30, was a ban on gambling by players or umpires.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] This served to discourage gambling by involved parties, although fan wagers were not mentioned in the guideline.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] However, section 33 banned bystanders from talking with players or umpires during play, unless by request of an umpire.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] In addition, the rules stated that players were required to be members of their clubs for 30 days before appearing in a game, and that they could play for only one team.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] These changes were made to avert a repeat of an 1856 game between the Gothams and Knickerbockers in which the Gothams had fielded a player who was a member of the Union Club at the same time, leading to protests by the Knickerbockers and criticism from the Union Club.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The customs of the day favored teams fielding nine-player squads in match games, although it was not specifically prescribed in existing rules and some games played outside the New York City area saw varying numbers of players.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Section 27 of the Laws codified the nine-player guideline, going against the wishes of the Knickerbockers, who had wanted the minimum player number set at seven.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Along with player and inning numbers, another item supported by the Knickerbockers that failed to make it past the rules committee was the "fly game", in which fielders who caught a batted ball on the fly would record an out, but not those who made a catch after the first bounce.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Under regulations of the time, an out was posted when a batted ball was caught after one bounce; this was known as the bound rule.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Adams himself was a strong proponent of the proposal.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The Knickerbockers proposed a compromise in which the fly game would apply to fair balls, but foul balls could be caught on a hop.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The committee rejected the proposal, leaving the bound game intact.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Newer clubs opposed the change due to a fear that fielders would wind up with hand injuries.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] They were joined by some established teams, as neither the Eagles nor Gotham backed the change.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] As part of the rules passed, baserunners were prohibited from advancing on balls caught on the fly; modern guidelines that allowed runners to tag up were not introduced until 1859.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] *Porter*'s had endorsed adding a regulation that would allow umpires to call strikes on batters "who did not swing at good pitches", but this also failed to gain a consensus.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The distance from the pitcher to home plate was extended two times after 1857; the second adjustment came in 1893.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] In March 1858, yet another meeting of clubs was held.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] There, as Adams wrote, "the annual convention was declared a permanent organization, and with the requisite constitution and by-laws", the National Association of Base Ball Players was formed.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] That year, another significant change was made to the rules, as called strikes were added.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The adjustment, along with the addition of called balls in 1863, made the pitcher a more significant factor than in previous years.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The fly game was debated for another seven years after 1857 before a one-year trial was adopted in 1864 for balls hit in fair territory.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] The rule, which was expanded to cover foul balls in 1883, remains in use in modern baseball.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Twenty-three pages from the "Laws" draft documents survived, having been kept by Grenelle's family.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] In 1999, they were sold to Frank Murray as part of a lot of vintage documents for $12,650.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] At the time, the authorship was not known.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] In 2015, Murray came forward to SCP Auctions, and analysis revealed the documents' authorship and significance.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] At an online auction the following year, the documents sold to Hayden Trubitt for over $3.2 million, the most that baseball-related papers had ever gone for at the time and more than three times what the auction house had estimated.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] In 2018-2019, the Laws appeared in a Library of Congress exhibition, having been loaned by Trubitt.
[src:doc-adams/1857-baseball-convention] Since May 2026, by virtue of a long-term loan from Trubitt, the documents have been on display at the National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum in Cooperstown, New York as part of the museum's "Rules of Base Ball" exhibit.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The **1858 Brooklyn–New York all-star game**, sometimes known as the "**Great Base Ball Match of 1858**", was a series of baseball contests between select standout players of from various amateur clubs in Manhattan and Brooklyn during the summer of 1858.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] In inviting only select players from multiple clubs, these games are now considered precursors to modern professional all-star games.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Hosted at the Fashion Course in Queens, the series is also noticeable for being the first baseball events to charge admission for spectators.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Brooklyn and New York faced off three times—on July 20, August 17, and September 10—with New York ultimately prevailing in the series, 2–1.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The number of amateur clubs in New York and Brooklyn grew from 6 in 1854 to about 24 the next year, with continued rapid expansion for the rest of the decade.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Sixteen New York–area clubs convened in 1857 to refine the standard rules, making fundamental decisions like setting the bases 90 feet apart.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] An outgrowth of this convention was the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP), the first baseball governing organization.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] In 1858, the NABBP decided to organize a series of games pitting the top players from New York and Brooklyn member clubs.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Match organizers sought to find a neutral hosting ground easily accessible by public transit; they settled on the Fashion Course horse racing grounds in Flushing, Queens, which was reachable by omnibus, rail, and trolley.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The course featured a grandstand, enabling spectators to sit in comfort.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The organizers created an all-dirt infield on the course by stripping away grass turf; the costs associated with landscaping the field and renting the facility incurred unexpected costs for the clubs.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] To cover these costs—and taking advantage of the gated entrances to the facility—the clubs decided to charge an admission fee of 10 cents for the event.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The 1858 matches thus became (in addition to being the first all-star games), the first to be played in an enclosed ground and the first to require paid admission.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The highly anticipated first match, on July 20, featured members of the Knickerbocker, Gotham, Eagle, Empire, Harlem, and Union clubs on the New York side, and members of the Atlantics, Excelsior, Putnam, and Eckford clubs from Brooklyn.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Among the New York players was Knickerbocker Harry Wright, who would be elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame nearly a century later.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Attendance estimates for this game range from 4,000–10,000.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The New York squad prevailed in the debut match, 22–18.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The game ball used in this match survives to this day and is in the possession of the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Both club managers made personnel changes after the first match.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Eckford of Brooklyn cofounder Frank Pidgeon was moved from shortstop to pitcher for this game.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Pidgeon's scorecard for the match survives today.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The Brooklyn stars routed New York, 29–8, evening the series.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] After its strong showing in the second match, Brooklyn left its lineup mostly intact for the rubber match.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] New York, however, made major lineup changes, including a change at pitcher.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Longtime Knickerbocker and baseball pioneer Doc Adams served as umpire and was the first umpire to apply an NABBP rule that called batters out after non-swinging strikes.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Frank Pidegon returned as pitcher for Brooklyn, logging 438 pitches during the match.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] New York won, 29–18, handing them the series victory.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Although the clubs did not seek or retain the profits, they proved that baseball was popular enough to become a profitable venture.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] A number of 1858 all-stars, including Harry Wright and William H.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Van Cott, participated in the "first-ever multi-club intercity tournament" in 1862, competing against Philadelphia clubs.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Although New York won the series, Brooklyn clubs proved to dominate local competition in the 1860s.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] By 1862, Bill Cammeyer established the first enclosed ballpark designed solely for baseball use—Union Grounds in Williamsburg—and began charging regular admission fees.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] By the end of the 1860s, baseball was in the process of becoming a professional industry, and in 1871 the NABBP was replaced by the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players—the first professional baseball league.
[src:doc-adams/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Major League Baseball played its first official all-star game in 1933.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Although he never made such a claim, Doubleday was declared to have invented the game of baseball in 1908, fifteen years after his death, by the Mills Commission.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] This claim has been thoroughly debunked by baseball historians.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday and Hester Donnelly, was born in Ballston Spa, New York, in a small house on the corner of Washington and Fenwick streets.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] The family all slept in the attic loft of the one-room house.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] His paternal grandfather, also named Abner, had fought in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] His maternal grandfather Thomas Donnelly had joined the army at 14 and was a mounted messenger for George Washington.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] His great-grandfather Peter Donnelly was a Minuteman.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] His father, Ulysses F., fought in the War of 1812, published newspapers and books, and represented Auburn, New York, for four years in the United States Congress.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Abner spent his childhood in Auburn and later was sent to Cooperstown to live with his uncle and attend a private preparatory high school.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] He practiced as a surveyor and civil engineer for two years before entering the United States Military Academy in 1838.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] He graduated in 1842, 24th in a class of 56 cadets, and was commissioned a brevet second lieutenant in the 3rd U.S.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] In 1852, he married Mary Hewitt of Baltimore, the daughter of a local lawyer.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday initially served in coastal garrisons and then in the Mexican–American War from 1846 to 1848 and the Seminole Wars from 1856 to 1858.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] In 1858, he was transferred to Fort Moultrie in Charleston Harbor serving under Colonel John L.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] By the start of the Civil War, he was a captain and second in command in the garrison at Fort Sumter, under Major Robert Anderson.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] He aimed the cannon that fired the first return shot in answer to the Confederate bombardment on April 12, 1861.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] He subsequently referred to himself as the "hero of Sumter" for this role.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Of note, although Doubleday did not invent baseball, by sheer coincidence the Fort Sumter Garrison Flag (or Storm Flag) has the star pattern arranged in a diamond shape, which by that time in history, was the shape of the baseball infield.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday was promoted to major on May 14, 1861, and commanded the Artillery Department in the Shenandoah Valley from June to August, and then the artillery for Major General Nathaniel Banks's division of the Army of the Potomac.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] He was appointed brigadier general of volunteers on February 3, 1862, and was assigned to duty in northern Virginia while the Army of the Potomac conducted the Peninsula Campaign.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] His first combat assignment was to lead the 2nd Brigade, 1st Division, III Corps of the Army of Virginia during the Northern Virginia Campaign.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] In the actions at Brawner's farm, just before the Second Battle of Bull Run, he took the initiative to send two of his regiments to reinforce Brigadier General John Gibbon's brigade against a larger Confederate force, fighting it to a standstill.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Personal initiative was required since his division commander, Brig.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Rufus King, was incapacitated by an epileptic seizure at the time.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] He was replaced by Brigadier General John P.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] His men were routed when they encountered Major General James Longstreet's corps, but by the following day, August 30, he took command of the division when Hatch was wounded, and he led his men to cover the retreat of the Union Army.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday again led the division, now assigned to the I Corps of the Army of the Potomac, after South Mountain, where Hatch was wounded again.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] He received a brevet promotion to lieutenant colonel in the regular army for his actions at Antietam and was promoted in March 1863 to major general of volunteers, to rank from November 29, 1862.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] At Fredericksburg in December 1862, his division mostly sat idle.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] During the winter, the I Corps was reorganized and Doubleday assumed command of the 3rd Division.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] At Chancellorsville in May 1863, the division was kept in reserve.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] At the start of the Battle of Gettysburg, July 1, 1863, Doubleday's division was the second infantry division on the field to reinforce the cavalry division of Brigadier General John Buford.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] When his corps commander, Major General John F.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Reynolds, was killed very early in the fighting, Doubleday found himself in command of the corps at 10:50 am.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] His men fought well in the morning, putting up a stout resistance, but as overwhelming Confederate forces massed against them, their line eventually broke and they retreated back through the town of Gettysburg to the relative safety of Cemetery Hill south of town.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] It was Doubleday's finest performance during the war, five hours leading 9,500 men against ten Confederate brigades that numbered more than 16,000.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Seven of those brigades sustained casualties that ranged from 35 to 50 percent, indicating the ferocity of the Union defense.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] On Cemetery Hill, however, the I Corps could muster only a third of its men as effective for duty, and the corps was essentially destroyed as a combat force for the rest of the battle; it would be decommissioned in March 1864, its surviving units consolidated into other corps.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] On July 2, 1863, Army of the Potomac commander Maj.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Meade replaced Doubleday with Major General John Newton, a more junior officer from another corps.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] The ostensible reason was a false report by XI Corps commander Major General Oliver O.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Howard that Doubleday's corps broke first, causing the entire Union line to collapse, but Meade also had a long history of disdain for Doubleday's combat effectiveness, dating back to South Mountain.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday was humiliated by this snub and held a lasting grudge against Meade, but he returned to division command and fought well for the remainder of the battle.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] He was wounded in the neck on the second day of Gettysburg and received a brevet promotion to colonel in the regular army for his service.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] He formally requested reinstatement as I Corps commander, but Meade refused, and Doubleday left Gettysburg on July 7 for Washington.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday's staff nicknamed him "Forty-Eight Hours" as a compliment to recognize his tendency to avoid reckless or impulsive actions and his thoughtfulness and deliberateness in considering circumstances and possible responses.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] In recent years, biographers have turned the nickname into an insult, incorrectly claiming "Forty-Eight Hours" was coined to highlight Doubleday's supposed incompetence and slowness to act.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday assumed administrative duties in the defenses of Washington, D.C., where he was in charge of courts martial, which gave him legal experience that he used after the war.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] His only return to combat was directing a portion of the defenses against the attack by Confederate Lieutenant General Jubal A.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Also while in Washington, Doubleday testified against George Meade at the United States Congress Joint Committee on the Conduct of the War, criticizing him harshly over his conduct of the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] While in Washington, Doubleday remained a loyal Republican and staunch supporter of President Abraham Lincoln.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday rode with Lincoln on the train to Gettysburg for the Gettysburg Address and Col. and Mrs.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday attended events with Mr. and Mrs.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday mustered out of the volunteer service after the Civil War on August 24, 1865, reverted to the rank of lieutenant colonel, and in September 1867 became the colonel of the 35th U.S.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] He was stationed in San Francisco from 1869 through 1871 and he took out a patent for the cable car railway that still runs there and received a charter for its operation, but signed away his rights when he was reassigned.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Infantry, an all African-American regiment with headquarters at Fort McKavett, Texas.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] He was listed in the New York business directory as a lawyer in the 1870s.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday spent much of his time writing.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] He published two important works on the Civil War: *Reminiscences of Forts Sumter and Moultrie* (1876), and *Chancellorsville and Gettysburg* (1882), the latter being a volume of the series *Campaigns of the Civil War*.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] In the summer of 1878, Doubleday lived in Mendham Township, New Jersey, and became a prominent member of the Theosophical Society.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] When Helena Blavatsky and Henry Steel Olcott, two of the founders of that society, moved to India at the end of that year, he was constituted as the president of the American body.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday died of heart disease in Mendham Township on January 26, 1893.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday's body was laid in state in New York's City Hall and then was taken to Washington by train from Mendham, and was buried in Arlington National Cemetery in Arlington County, Virginia.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Although Doubleday achieved minor fame as a competent combat general with experience in many important Civil War battles, he is more widely known as the supposed inventor of the game of baseball, supposed to have invented the game in 1839 in Elihu Phinney's cow pasture in Cooperstown, New York.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] The Mills Commission, chaired by Abraham G.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Mills, the fourth president of the National League, was appointed idiosyncratically in 1905 to determine the origin of baseball.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] However, there is considerable evidence to dispute this claim.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Chairman Mills himself, who had been a Civil War colleague of Doubleday and a member of the honor guard for Doubleday's body as it lay in state in New York City, never recalled hearing Doubleday describe his role as the inventor.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday was a cadet at West Point in the year of the alleged invention and his family had moved away from Cooperstown the prior year.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Furthermore, the primary testimony to the commission that connected baseball to Doubleday was that of Abner Graves, whose credibility is questionable.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] In the years after he gave his testimony, Graves shot his wife to death and was committed to an institution for the criminally insane for the rest of his life.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Part of the confusion could stem from there being another man by the same name in Cooperstown in 1839.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Despite the lack of solid evidence linking Doubleday to the origins of baseball, Cooperstown, New York, became the new home of what is today the National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum in 1937.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] There may have been some relationship to baseball as a national sport and Abner Doubleday.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] In his capacity as a high-ranking officer, whose duties included seeing to provisions for the U.S.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Army fighting throughout the South and border states, Doubleday is said to have provisioned balls and bats for the morale of the men.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday's men, admirers, and the state of New York erected a monument to him at Gettysburg.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] There is a 7-foot (2.1 m) obelisk monument at Arlington National Cemetery where he is buried.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] Doubleday Field is a 9,791-seat baseball stadium named for Abner Doubleday, located in Cooperstown, New York, near the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] It hosted the annual Hall of Fame Game, an exhibition game between two major league teams that was played from 1940 until 2008, and has hosted the Hall of Fame Classic since 2009.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] The Auburn Doubledays are a collegiate summer baseball team based in Doubleday's hometown of Auburn, New York.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] At the United States Military Academy at West Point, New York, where the Army Black Knights play at Johnson Stadium, Doubleday Field is named in Doubleday's honor.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] In Ballston Spa, New York, the town of his birth, Doubleday Fields are named for Doubleday.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] The house of his birth still stands in the middle of town and there is a monument to him on Front Street.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] At the Doubleday Hill Monument, a sign to commemorate Doubleday's occupation of a hill in Williamsport, Maryland during the Civil War claims he invented the game in 1835.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] For numerous years, Mendham Borough and Mendham Township, New Jersey has held a municipal holiday known as "Abner Doubleday Day" in the General's honor and in 1998 commissioned a plaque near the site of his home in the borough, even though the borough was known as Mendham Township back then.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] The Abner Doubleday Society erected a monument to Doubleday in Iron Spring Park near his birthplace in Ballston Spa in 2004.
[src:doc-adams/abner-doubleday] In World War II, the United States Liberty ship SS *Abner Doubleday* was named in his honor.
[src:doc-adams/africa-cup-baseball-championship] The **Africa Cup Baseball Championship** is the main international baseball competition in Africa.
[src:doc-adams/africa-cup-baseball-championship] The Africa Cup Baseball Championship has not been played with the frequency, regularity, or history of the European Championship, Asian Championship or South American Championship.
[src:doc-adams/africa-cup-baseball-championship] Instead, it has been more irregular, like the Oceania Championship.
[src:doc-adams/africa-cup-baseball-championship] Contintental tournaments were also held at the All-Africa Games in 1999 and 2003.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] The rules of the modern game were long considered to have been based on the Knickerbocker Rules developed in 1845 by Cartwright and a committee from the Knickerbockers.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] However, later research called this scenario into question.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] The myth of Abner Doubleday having invented baseball was believed by many, but in Cooperstown in 1939, the myth was debunked.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Cartwright (unlike Doubleday) was inducted into the Hall of Fame as a pioneering contributor to the game, 46 years after his death.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Although it has been stated that Cartwright was officially declared the inventor of the modern game of baseball by the 83rd United States Congress on June 3, 1953, the *Congressional Record*, the *House Journal*, and the *Senate Journal* from June 3, 1953, did not mention Cartwright.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Cartwright was born in 1820 to Alexander Cartwright Sr.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] He first worked at the age of 16 in 1836 as a clerk for a Wall Street broker, later doing clerical work at the Union Bank of New York.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] After hours, he played bat-and-ball games in the streets of Manhattan with volunteer firefighters.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Cartwright himself was a volunteer, first with Oceana Hose Company No.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] 36, and then Knickerbocker Engine Company No.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Cartwright's ancestor Thomas Cartwright, of Aynho Park, Northamptonshire was an English landowner and Tory politician, who sat in the English and British House of Commons between 1695 and 1748.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] As the longest serving member he was dubbed Father of the House.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] A fire destroyed the Union Bank in 1845, forcing Cartwright to find other work.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] He became a bookseller with his brother, Alfred.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] One of the earliest known established clubs was the Gotham Base Ball Club, who played a brand of bat-and-ball game often called "town ball" or "round ball," but in New York more usually "base ball," similar but not identical to the British sport of rounders, on a field at 4th Avenue and 27th Street.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Wheaton drew up rules converting this playground game into a more elaborate and interesting sport to be played by adults.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] In 1842, Cartwright led the establishment of the Knickerbocker Base Ball Club (named after the Knickerbocker Fire Engine Company), a breakaway group from the Gothams.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] In 1845, a committee from the new club including Wheaton (but not Cartwright) drew up rules resembling those of the Gothams.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] The major precepts included the stipulations that foul territories were to be introduced for the first time, and the practice of retiring a runner by hitting him with a thrown ball was forbidden.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Cartwright is also erroneously credited for introducing flat bases at uniform distances, three strikes per batter, and nine players in the outfield.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] However, modern scholarship has cast doubt on the originality of these rules, as information has come to light about the New York clubs that predated the Knickerbockers, in particular the rules devised by William R.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Baseball historian Jeffrey Kittel has concluded that none of the Knickerbocker Rules of 1845 was original, with the possible exception of three-out innings.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] As MLB's Official Historian John Thorn wrote, Cartwright has "a plaque in the Baseball Hall of Fame on which every word of substance is false.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Alex Cartwright did not set the base paths at ninety feet, the sides at nine men, or the game at nine innings." (In fact, all three were established by the inter-club Convention of 1857, eight years after Cartwright had left New York).
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] The first clearly documented match between two baseball clubs under these rules took place on June 19, 1846, at Elysian Fields in Hoboken, New Jersey.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] In this match, the Knickerbockers lost to the "New York nine" (probably the parent Gotham Club) by a score of 23 to 1.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Some authors have also questioned the supposed "first game" under the new rules.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] The Knickerbockers' scorebook shows intra-club games during 1845; the New York Base Ball Club played at least three games against a Brooklyn club in 1845 also, but the rules used are unknown.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Those who have studied the score-book have concluded that the differences in the games of 1845 and 1846, compared with the specifications of the Knickerbocker rules, are minimal.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] In 1849, Cartwright headed to California for the gold rush, and then continued on to work and live in the Kingdom of Hawaii.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Their sons Bruce Cartwright (1853–1919) and Alexander Joy Cartwright III (1855–1921) were born in Hawaii.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Some secondary sources claim Cartwright set up a baseball field on the island of Oahu at Makiki Field in 1852, but Nucciarone states that before 1866, the modern game of baseball was not known or even played in Honolulu.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Also, she states that during Cartwright's lifetime he was not declared or documented as an originator of baseball in Hawaii.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Cartwright served as fire chief of Honolulu from 1850 through June 30, 1863.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] He was an advisor to King David Kalākaua and Queen Emma.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Cartwright died on July 12, 1892, six months before the overthrow of the Hawaiian monarchy in 1893.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] One of the leaders of the overthrow movement was Lorrin A.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Thurston, who played baseball with classmate Alexander Cartwright III at Punahou School.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] After about two decades of controversy, invention of America's "national game" of baseball was attributed to Abner Doubleday by the Mills Commission (1905–1907).
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Some baseball historians promptly cried foul and others joined throughout the 20th century.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Cartwright was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1938.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Henderson documented Cartwright's contributions to baseball in his 1947 book *Bat, Ball, and Bishop*.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Although there is no question that Cartwright was a prominent figure in the early development of baseball, some students of baseball history have suggested that Henderson and others embellished Cartwright's role.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] The primary complaint is that touting Cartwright as the "true" inventor of the modern game was an effort to find an alternative single individual to counter the "invention" of baseball by Abner Doubleday.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Cartwright was the subject of a 1973 biography, *The Man Who Invented Baseball*, by Harold Peterson.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] He was the subject of two biographies written in 2009.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] The 2004 discovery of a newspaper interview with fellow Knickerbocker founder William R.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Wheaton cast doubt on Cartwright's role.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] Wheaton stated that most of the rules long attributed to Cartwright and the Knickerbockers had in fact been developed by the older Gotham Club before the Knickerbockers' founding.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] In 1938, Makiki Field in Honolulu was renamed Cartwright Field.
[src:doc-adams/alexander-cartwright] The Cartwright Cup is awarded to the Hawaii state high school baseball champions each year.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Born in the city of Quebec, Canada, Al Spink and his two brothers learned baseball's English cousin, cricket.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] The family of ten moved to Chicago after the American Civil War and the boys moved to baseball, whose boom was continental in scope.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] In 1869 or 1870, the Spinks founded the amateur Mutual club on the West Side, named after the professional Mutuals of New York.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Probably there were dozens of amateur clubs in Chicago beside the professional White Stockings.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Older brother Billy (William C.) became sporting editor of the *St.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Louis Globe-Democrat* and persuaded Al to move to that city in 1875, where he was soon covering baseball for the Missouri, later St.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] The city's first fully professional baseball team, the original St.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Louis Brown Stockings were then in operation, contesting the championship of the U.S. in the National Association and then the National League.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Not long after the Browns went out of business in December 1877, the Spink brothers began thinking about how to restore professional baseball in their city.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Unfortunately, spectator interest in the game had been damaged by the scandal that persuaded the Browns to drop out, and they struggled to organize a team of former pros playing cooperatively.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Al Spink helped turn the trick in 1881, establishing the Sportsman's Park and Club Association with Chris von der Ahe, whose first work was to acquire and renovate the old Grand Avenue ballpark (as Sportsman's Park).
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Spink organized a new Brown Stockings team and booked games with other western teams, especially one organized by Cincinnati baseball writer O.P.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Caylor and billed as the Cincinnati Red Stockings.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] The success of independent commercial baseball in 1881, especially in St.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Louis, inspired organization of the American Association league for 1882, with Sportsman's Park and Club its member from St.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] The writers Spink and Caylor remained influential although the clubs were owned by men of "greater substance".
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Al Spink founded *The Sporting News* in March 1886.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Each number was 17 by 22 inches, eight pages, price five cents (Cooper 1996).
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] The leading baseball newspapers were then based in the East, the weeklies *Clipper* and *Sporting Life* in New York and Philadelphia.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] By World War I, *TSN* would be the only national baseball newspaper.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Al Spink had long turned it over to his younger brother Charles, hiring Charles as business manager in the 1880s, selling his stock in 1894, and finally departing from writing and editorial work in 1899 (Cooper 1996).
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Taylor Spink, took over *The Sporting News* in 1914.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Some time after leaving *TSN*, Al moved to Chicago where he would eventually write for the *Evening Post*.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] In 1910, revised in 1911, he published one of the first baseball histories, *The National Game*.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] One section organized by city is full of detail on early amateur and independent organizations and players, including 20 pages for his adopted city, "The Game in St.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Another section consists of short entries on more than one hundred baseball writers with dozens of portrait photos.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] The sections on players organized by fielding position are not unique, but they remain a treasure trove because Spink did not focus exclusively on major league players or major league spans of careers.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Spink died 1928 in Oak Park, Illinois, almost 74 years old.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] He was the uncle of sportswriter Ernest J.
[src:doc-adams/alfred-henry-spink] Lanigan, who compiled the first encyclopedia of baseball, *The Baseball Cyclopedia*.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] From 1847 to 1861, the Knickerbockers selected Adams as their president six times, and as a vice president, treasurer, or director in six other years.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] As president of the club, Adams was an advocate of rule changes in baseball that resulted in nine-man teams and nine-inning games.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] When the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP) was formed in 1858, he led the rules and regulations committee of the new organization.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In his role, Adams ruled that the fields' bases should be 90 feet (27 m) apart, the modern distance, and supported the elimination of the "bound rule", which allowed for balls caught after one bounce to be recorded as outs.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He resigned from his positions with the Knickerbockers and NABBP in 1862.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams' contributions in creating baseball's rules went largely unrecognized for decades after his 1899 death, but in 1980 a letter about him appeared in *The New York Times*; by 1993, researcher John Thorn had written about Adams' role.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Other historians have given him credit for helping to develop the sport, and Thorn has called Adams "first among the Fathers of Baseball".
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] A graduate of Yale University and Harvard Medical School, Adams began working in the medical field in the late 1830s, and practiced in New York City during his time as a member of the Knickerbockers.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In 1865, he left medicine and later became a bank president and member of the Connecticut legislature.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Born in Mont Vernon, New Hampshire, on November 1, 1814, Adams was the fourth of Daniel and Nancy Adams' five children.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The elder Daniel Adams was a physician and author; he wrote a math textbook that was widely used in the United States in the early- to mid-1800s.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] After being schooled at Kimball Union Academy in New Hampshire from 1826 to 1828 and Amherst, Massachusetts' Mount Pleasant Classical Institution, Adams attended three colleges from 1831 to 1838.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He studied at Amherst College for two years, then transferred to Yale University, where he acquired a bachelor's degree upon his graduation in 1835.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Nancy Adams, Daniel's sister, indicated in a letter penned in the early 1830s that he began playing with "bats and balls" by this time.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams continued his studies at Harvard Medical School through 1838, obtaining an MD.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Following his time in college, he joined his father's medical practice.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The pair worked in Mont Vernon, before the younger Adams relocated twice, first to Boston and then to New York City.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams also worked for the New York Dispensaries, which provided medical care to poor residents.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He offered his assistance when outbreaks of cholera affected New York City.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] For providing vaccinations, Adams received yearly pay of $400 for a time.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] His field of employment gave rise to his nickname of "Doc", which was given as "Dock" at the time.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] According to baseball historian John Thorn, 1839 is the year Adams became a baseball player.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In an 1896 interview in *The Sporting News*, Adams said that "soon after going to New York I began to play base ball just for exercise, with a number of other young medical men." Starting in 1840, he was a player with the New York Base Ball Club.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] This team had been founded in 1837, eight years earlier than the New York Knickerbockers, who are credited in several baseball histories as pioneering the modern version of baseball.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams played an early form of the game, but Thorn writes that he "understood [it] to be baseball, no matter what it was called".
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams received an invitation to become a member of the Knickerbockers a month or so after the team's September 23, 1845, creation.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He accepted and joined the club along with other men in the medical field; he later said that players from the New York Base Ball Club were behind the formation of the Knickerbockers.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Records of the club's practice games indicate that he was a member of the Knickerbockers by November 18, 1845.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In an inter-squad game held that day, which was the Knickerbockers' last of the year, Adams scored nine runs for his team as they defeated a side picked by William R.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The club organized its first game against outside opposition in 1846; at a June 5 meeting Adams was selected to a three-man committee whose aim was to set up a game against the New York Base Ball Club.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The committee's efforts were successful, and a game was scheduled on June 19.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams participated in the contest, which the Knickerbockers lost 23–1.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Batting second in the Knickerbockers' lineup, he made one out and did not score a run.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The Knickerbockers did not play any known games against other clubs from 1847 to 1850.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] During these years, the team split its players into two squads, which played against each other twice per week.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] According to Adams, he often attempted to compel members of the Knickerbockers to attend the sessions.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He was only occasionally successful, and when few Knickerbockers came, they played variants of baseball that required fewer players than regular games.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Twice in June 1851, the club played against the Washington Base Ball Club, winning by scores of 21–11 and 22–20.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] No individual statistics are available for the first game; Adams scored twice for the Knickerbockers in the second.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In 1853, Adams played in two games against the Gotham Ball Club, tallying seven runs in a pair of victories.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The two clubs met three times from June to October 1854, and Adams had one run in each game.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] After splitting the first two contests, their October 26, 1854, game lasted 12 innings before being suspended due to darkness with the score tied 12–12; both teams fell short of the 21 runs that were required to win a game under the rules of the time.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Following two November games against the Eagle Base Ball Club that Adams is not known to have participated in, he returned to the Knickerbockers' lineup for a June 1, 1855, game against Gotham and scored three times, although Gotham prevailed, 21–12.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He took part in two other 1855 games against Eagle and Gotham, respectively, scoring five runs total as the Knickerbockers won both contests.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams competed four times for the club against outside opponents in 1856 as it won once, lost twice, and had one tie; he scored ten times, and records for two games showed that his defensive position was shortstop.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The Knickerbockers had a 2–2 win–loss record in competitive games during 1857 that Adams participated in.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Playing three times at shortstop and once at first base defensively, he contributed 12 runs offensively, including a six-run effort in the Knickerbockers' 37–23 victory over the Empire club on June 24.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In 1858, Adams made four appearances for the Knickerbockers against outside opposition and scored nine runs, but the team went 1–3 in the games.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He varied his defensive positioning between second base, third base, and shortstop.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] As a player, Adams created the concept of the shortstop position, according to Thorn and Baseball Hall of Fame researcher Freddy Berowski.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In the first five years the Knickerbockers played, the team fielded anywhere from eight to eleven players.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The only infielders were the players covering each of the bases; if there were more than eight players, extra outfielders were sometimes used.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The outfielders had difficulty throwing baseballs into the infield, because of the balls' light weight.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams' shortstop position, at which he started playing in about 1849 or 1850, was used to field throws from the outfielders and throw to the three infielders.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] With the advent of higher-quality baseballs, Adams moved toward the infield, since the distance the balls could travel increased.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Prior to the invention of the shortstop, large gaps existed in the defensive positioning of infields; defensive players tended to stand by bases, leaving empty space in between them for batters.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The shortstop filled one of the two gaps.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams hit left-handed; he said that his batted balls occasionally went into a river by the Elysian Fields, the ground in Hoboken, New Jersey, where the Knickerbockers practiced and played.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams had a long on-field career with the Knickerbockers; he remained a player with the team until 1859.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He did not limit his play to shortstop; he fielded at every position except pitcher.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Little is known about the relative performance of early baseball players, and the game was largely recreational, as opposed to competitive.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Thorn speculates that Adams may have been "the best player of the 1840s", citing his lengthy playing career as evidence.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In addition to playing the game, Adams was involved in the production of early baseball equipment.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He personally manufactured baseballs for a period of time, supplying many New York City-based clubs.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams found that when the ball was more tightly stitched, it traveled further when batted or thrown.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] According to author Peter Morris, Adams' ball-manufacturing efforts helped to keep the Knickerbockers in operation during their first few years, as they would otherwise have had difficulty finding balls.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In later years Adams gathered rubber from old galoshes for the insides of baseballs.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] A tanner then used horsehide to create the balls.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] As late as 1863, Adams was one of the three most prominent makers of baseballs in New York, continuing to produce them by hand.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams also played a role in producing baseball bats, choosing which wood to use and overseeing the manufacturing process.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams also worked occasionally as an umpire in significant games.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] One notable example was the final contest of a three-game series between all-star teams from Brooklyn and New York City, held on September 10, 1858, in Long Island.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] During the game, which the New York City all-stars won 29–18, Adams became the first umpire to use a new rule allowing for a strike to be called against a batter who refused to swing when "good pitches" were thrown to them.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Previously, strikes were only called when a batter swung at a pitch and missed.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Three batters were ruled out on strikes called by Adams in the game.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Otherwise, the called strike rule was not applied often in its first few years of existence.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The Knickerbockers held elections annually to determine who would serve as officials.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] At the club's second election, held on May 5, 1846, Adams was named the Knickerbockers' vice president.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] At an April 1847 meeting, he became the president of the team, and was re-elected in 1848 and 1849.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He was the leader of a "Committee to Revive the Constitution and By-Laws" of baseball in 1848.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams was not chosen as an officer in 1851, but the next year was named one of the club's three treasurers; he was elected to the same position the following two years.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The number of baseball teams in the New York City area started to grow during the early 1850s, as the Washington Base Ball Club (also known as the Gotham Ball Club) and Eagle Base Ball Club were founded or reorganized.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The Eagle Base Ball Club, desiring a unified set of rules, sent a message to the Knickerbockers requesting that a committee be formed.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams was one of the three Knickerbockers members selected to be on the committee, and the clubs agreed on a set of rules, which were presented at the Knickerbockers' meeting on April 1, 1854.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] At the same meeting, Adams was voted into the position of club director.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] After again being named a director in 1855, Adams became president of the Knickerbockers for the fourth time, winning an election held at the club's April 5, 1856, meeting.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He remained the team's president in 1857, and after not being named as an officer the next three years, was elected president in 1861.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] During his time as the club's president, the Knickerbockers' organization was emulated by newly formed teams, and Adams himself was considered a "respected" figure by members of other clubs.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Schiff, Adams was among the most powerful baseball figures of the era.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Concurrently, Adams maintained his New York City medical practice.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] A supporter of nine-man baseball teams, Adams favored a measure in 1856 which allowed for players from outside the Knickerbockers to join their intrasquad games when 17 or fewer team members appeared.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] No rules existed at the time regarding team size, but official games between clubs were typically played with nine men per club.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The proposal was defeated by a 13–11 vote, in favor of a rule forbidding non-club members to play if there were 14 players (seven per team).
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] A two-man committee was created with the aim of working with the Eagle and Washington clubs to resolve the debate over how many players to field in official games.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Ladd were chosen as the committee members, but Ladd withdrew and Adams was named as a substitute.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] His partner on the committee, Curry, had led the opposition to nine-man teams.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams and Curry also differed on another issue: the length of games.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] At the time, a baseball game lasted until one of the teams had 21 runs; that team was awarded the victory.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] A change in how games were won was deemed necessary after the suspended game in 1854.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams favored nine-inning games, while Curry wanted contests to last seven innings.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] A convention was scheduled for early 1857, and Adams joined a three-man committee tasked with encouraging local clubs to send delegates.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] At the convention, which consisted of one session each in January and February, Adams was voted president.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The Knickerbockers had voted among themselves to back seven-inning games, but the other teams backed a motion for nine-inning contests, which passed.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] These changes were incorporated in the "Laws of Base Ball", written by Adams.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He authored the initial draft of the regulations with what *The New York Times'* Richard Sandomir called "an upright script and strong hand." The "Laws" included regulations governing bat and ball sizes, and a ban on betting by players and umpires.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Grenelle copied Adams' work onto blue pages, and modifications and notations were made as the convention progressed.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Among other changes, part of the rule Adams had written on game length was crossed out; the number nine was replaced with seven, before the motion that settled the issue was introduced.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In March, the Knickerbockers changed their rules to match those passed at the convention.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In May 1857, Adams presided over a player convention where nine-inning games were officially made part of the rules of baseball for participating teams.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In March 1858, the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP) was formed at another convention.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams was one of the Knickerbockers' two delegates, having been selected at a February meeting attended by representatives from 25 clubs.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He held the chairmanship of the association's rules and regulations committee, and drafted the new organization's initial set of rules.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] These included a clarification of the prescribed distance between bases, which under Knickerbocker Rules had been set at "forty-two paces" between home plate and second base, and "forty-two paces, equidistant" between first and third base.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Historians differ on whether the bases were roughly 90 feet (27 m) apart, or a shorter distance.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He ruled on the distance between home plate and the pitcher's position as well, making them 45 feet (14 m) apart.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In addition, the committee mandated that clubs have nine players per side, which became the norm.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] It also created the called strike rule, in an effort to reduce pitch totals and the time required to play games.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams campaigned for a further change in the rules of baseball, involving when outs were recorded.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] At the time, an out was allowed when the ball was caught by a fielder after one bounce; this was known as the "bound rule".
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams supported a ban on such outs, calling his preferred rule "the fly-game".
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Under the style of play he backed, when a fly ball was hit a fielder would have to catch the ball before it touched the ground for an out to be made.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] This was similar to rules on catches in cricket, and would serve to increase the level of skill required from fielders.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The Knickerbockers had enacted a rule mandating the "fly-catch" by 1857.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The Knickerbockers attempted to introduce the fly rule more widely at the 1857 convention, with a proposal that permitted the continued use of the bound rule for foul balls.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Despite widespread support from sportswriters, the proposed rule change was voted down.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Writer William Hershberger said that the decision showed "the limits of the Knickerbockers' influence and divisions within the baseball fraternity." The rule change was proposed to the NABBP annually by Adams but did not pass.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] At the 1858 NABBP convention, a vote on eliminating the bound rule was unsuccessful.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Opponents raised concerns that the proposal would dramatically lengthen game times.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Despite his support for the fly rule, in 1858 Adams successfully motioned for NABBP regulations, including outs on bounces, to apply to the Knickerbockers.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He did so because he was reluctant to oppose the rules of the NABBP.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Shortly after his motion, he organized a Knickerbockers meeting to discuss the fly rule and "obtain a reconsideration" of the newly passed resolution.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] At the meeting, the Knickerbockers decided to exclude outs on bounces from their practice games and contests against teams that supported the fly rule.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In future years, the club remained an advocate of eliminating the bound rule, but Adams' continued efforts were rejected.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] A split in the rules and regulations committee caused it to avoid supporting the fly game at the NABBP's 1859 convention, and votes at the 1860 and 1861 conventions maintained the bound rule.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams' final comments about the regulation at an NABBP convention indicated that he believed it would soon be modified.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The bound rule started losing support by 1863, after Adams left the Knickerbockers, and outs on bounced balls were outlawed in 1864.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In addition to his other roles, Adams regularly served as a delegate on behalf of the Knickerbockers at the NABBP's annual meetings.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He remained with the Knickerbockers in an executive role until March 26, 1862, when he retired having served 12 years overall in various non-playing capacities.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Upon leaving his position, the club named him an honorary member.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He received a scroll from the Knickerbockers, which referred to him as "The Nestor of Ball Players", alluding to a mythical king known for offering advice and for his long life.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams also resigned from his role as rules committee chairman of the NABBP.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams and Cornelia Cook married in 1861, and remained together until Adams' death.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The couple had five children; the first, a son named Charles, died less than a month after his birth in 1864.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The others, two sons (Frank and Roger) and two daughters (Catharine and Mary), were born between 1866 and 1874.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams continued to maintain his medical practice during his baseball career, but was forced to abandon it in 1865 after he began suffering health issues.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] After relocating to Ridgefield, Connecticut, he went on to become "one of the leading citizens of the Connecticut village," according to author William J.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams served as a Republican legislator in the Connecticut House of Representatives for the town in 1870.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He contributed to the creation of the Ridgefield Land Improvement Association, and to a committee overseeing construction of a town house.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In 1871, he accepted a job with the Ridgefield Savings Bank (later renamed the Fairfield County Bank) as the company's first president.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] After working there until 1879, Adams took a break from his duties; during this time, he helped found Ridgefield's library and served as its treasurer.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In 1884, he returned to the Ridgefield National Bank and remained president there until mid-1886.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams and his family relocated to a house in New Haven, Connecticut, in 1888.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Along with baseball, playing music was among Adams' favorite activities.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Occasionally, he and Henry Ward Beecher performed flute duets.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Although no longer actively involved in baseball, Adams was still a follower of the sport.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He played in an exhibition as late as 1875, and stories exist that he played recreationally into the following decade.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Late in his life, he said of the growth of baseball, "We pioneers never expected to see the game so universal as it has now become." Adams contracted pneumonia following a bout of influenza, and died on January 3, 1899, at the age of 84.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He was buried at New Haven's Evergreen Cemetery.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] For decades after Adams' death, his role in codifying baseball's early rules was largely unremembered.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Thorn included Adams among a group of "powerfully influential figures" from the period—also including Louis F.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Wadsworth and Wheaton—who he writes "went unrecognized in their lifetimes and became mysteries to future generations." Alexander Cartwright was more widely recognized as a pioneering figure for the sport.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The Baseball Hall of Fame has claimed that Cartwright was the inventor of 90-foot (27 m) baselines and the nine-inning game.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] However, by the time conventions led by Adams had enacted those rules in the late 1850s, Cartwright had traveled to California and was no longer a member of the Knickerbockers.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The 45-foot (14 m) distance from home plate to the pitching mound, however, did not last through the 19th century; it was pushed back 5 feet (1.5 m) in 1880.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The shortstop position, which for Adams was located between the infielders and outfielders, was later played in the infield, between second and third base.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Dickey Pearce was the first player to field in that area, and his ability to prevent base hits in the formerly unoccupied territory convinced other teams to employ similar tactics.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The *Hartford Courant* points to 1980 as a year when Adams started to gain greater attention for his achievements.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] A share of the New York Mets was purchased by a publishing company led by Nelson Doubleday Jr. that year, and claims that Abner Doubleday invented baseball in 1839, which are considered flawed by modern researchers, were reported by the media.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] After the Doubleday reports in 1980, *The New York Times* received a letter from the great-great-grandson of Adams that the *Courant* said attempted "to try to set the record straight." The newspaper ran the letter in its April 13 issue, and added a 1939 piece by Roger Adams.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] In 1993, Thorn published research on Adams' contributions in the encyclopedia *Total Baseball*.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] *The New York Times* published an article on Adams on September 23, 2015.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Mont Vernon holds an annual baseball game in honor of Adams, which incorporates the rules of his era, as a part of the town's Lamson Farm Day.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Various historians have given Adams recognition as an important figure from the early years of baseball.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] On July 31, 2014, the Society for American Baseball Research announced that it had chosen Adams as its 2014 "Overlooked 19th Century Baseball Legend".
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Eric Miklich has called him worthy of induction into the Baseball Hall of Fame for his role as a pioneer.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He says of Adams, "Should he be in the Hall of Fame?
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] You ask anyone who knows about 19th century baseball.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] They'll laugh at Cartwright; Abner Doubleday, they won't even talk about; but they all know Doc Adams.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] He was the glue that held things together in the early part of baseball." Adams did not appear on a Baseball Hall of Fame ballot until 2016, when he was up for consideration on the Hall's Pre-Integration Era Committee ballot.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Ten of the 16 committee members supported him, two fewer than the number needed for induction.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] While Adams' contributions had received notice from historians, Associated Press writer Andrew Dalton called such reports "somewhat speculative" in nature before 2016.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] That year, the 1857 "Laws of Base Ball" authored by Adams were sold at an auction.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] The documents were included in a batch of historical papers that brought $12,000 in a 1999 sale.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] Adams' authorship of the papers was unknown at the time, but was confirmed after the owner brought the documents to the attention of an auction house in 2015.
[src:doc-adams/doc-adams] An anonymous buyer purchased the "Laws of Base Ball" in April 2016 for $3.26 million, the most a series of baseball documents had ever sold for.
